MINNA – A Minna, Niger State High Court yesterday sentenced eleven persons to death by hanging for the brutal murder of seven villagers over land dispute in Lavun Local Government Area of the state. The 11 accussed persons to die by hanging, pronounced guilty of 7 count charges of murder and conspiracy to commit murder and culpable humicide under section 221, 229 of the panel code includes; Mohammed Mohammed, Baba Mohammed, Mohammed Isa, Abubakar Saba, Adamu Babaminin, and Ibrahim Emigi. Haruna Mohammed, Isah Madu, Ndama Sheshi Isah Mohammed and Mohammed Ndabida are also among the 26 persons charged to the court for the murder of the 7 persons in an attack at Gaba village from Afani village over disputed farm land between the two communities in 2019. Fight Against Drugs: Group Applauds Marwa Strategies Tension As Gun Men Kill Anambra Official Delivering judgement, Justice Maimuna Talatu Abubakar, held that the prosecutor proved beyond reasonable doubts that the charges against the accused persons and the accused persons did not deserved the clemency of the court considering the grievous of the offence and the manner in which the murder was carried out. She nevertheless acquitted 15 other accused persons for lack of convincing evidence. “I don’t think in this circumstance, there is extenuating basis for which the Court makes recommendations, consequently, on the 1st to 7th count charges of conspiracy and culpable humicide by causing the death of 7 deceased persons”. While insisting that justice must take its full course on the murderers, Justice Maimuna declared, “I hereby sentenced you to death by hanging until you die. May Allah have mercy on your souls”.